har2.htm\n| title = Silchar Climatological Table 1971\u20132000\n| publisher = India Meteorological Department\n| accessdate = 6 February 2020}}</ref>\n|source 2 = Tokyo Climate Center (mean temperatures 1981\u20132010)<ref name=TCC>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200229204133/https://ds.data.jma.go.jp/gmd/tcc/tcc/products/climate/normal/parts/NrmMonth_e.php?stn=42619\n| archivedate = 29 February 2020\n| url = https://ds.data.jma.go.jp/gmd/tcc/tcc/products/climate/normal/parts/NrmMonth_e.php?stn=42619\n| title = Normals Data: Silchar - India Latitude: 24.75\u00b0N Longitude: 92.80\u00b0E Height: 20 (m)\n| publisher = Japan Meteorological Agency\n| accessdate = 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n|date=April 2015}}\n\n== Education ==\n\n===University===\nSilchar is home to the main campus of [[Assam University]], a central university, which imparts education in both the general as well as professional streams. The university, which came into existence in 1994, has 17 schools and 35 post-graduate departments under them. The university has 56 affiliated colleges under it.<ref name=aus>{{cite web|title=Assam University, Homepage|url=http://www.aus.ac.in/|work=Assam University|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=aus1>{{cite web|title=Statistical Data Fact Sheet of AUS|url=http://www.aus.ac.in/STATISTICAL_DATA_FACT_SHEET_OF_AUS.pdf|work=Assam University|publisher=Assam University|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> The colleges in Silchar are mostly affiliated with the Assam university.\n\n===Technical institutions===\n* [[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]]\n[[File:Nit-silchar1.jpg|thumbnail|right|National Institute of Technology Silchar|211x211px]]\n* [http://www.aus.ac.in/TSSOT/ Triguna Sen School of Technology, Assam University, Silchar]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aus.ac.in/TSSOT/|title=TSSOT|publisher=|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n* Silchar Polytechnic<ref>http://silcharpolytechnic.in/</ref>\n* NIAIMT<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.natrip.in/index.php/2013-06-29-11-35-28/niaimt-silchar|title=NIAIMT Silchar|author=Super User|publisher=|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Colleges===\n\n* [[Guru Charan College]]\n* [[Cachar College]]\n* [[Women's College, Silchar|Women's College]]\n* [[Radhamadhab College]]\n* Silchar College<ref>http://www.dheassam.gov.in/circulars-1/meeting%2057.pdf retrieved on 14 January 2015</ref>\n*[http://www.ramanujcollege.ac.in Ramanuj Gupta Junior College]\n* Lalit jain commerce college<ref>http://www.dheassam.gov.in/circulars-1/meeting%2057.pdf retrieved on 14 January 2015</ref>\n\n===Medical college===\n* [[Silchar Medical College and Hospital]], established in 1968, serves the southern region of Assam. There is an Institute of Pharmacy attached to it.<ref name=smc>{{cite web|title=Silchar Medical College, Home Page|url=http://www.smcassam.gov.in|work=Silchar Medical College|publisher=Silchar Medical College|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Law colleges===\n* [[A. K. Chanda Law College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highereducationinindia.com/institutes/a-k-chanda-law-college-1879.php|title=A. K. Chanda Law College|publisher=|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> at Tarapur.\n\n==Airway transport==\n[[Silchar Airport]] (IXS) is located at Kumbhirgram, about 22&nbsp;km from Silchar.  Silchar has been selected as one of the towns for the construction of 51 low-cost airports across the country recently.<ref name=dna28jun>{{cite news|title=51 new low-cost airports to be set up: PMO|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-51-new-low-cost-airports-to-be-set-up-pmo-1854583|accessdate=3 March 2014|newspaper=Daily News & Analysis|date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1985, [[Air India]] operated the first all-woman crew flight in the world from Kolkata to Silchar which was commanded by Captain Saudamini Deshmukh on a [[Fokker F-27 Friendship]] aircraft.<ref name=\"TOI11\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-03-08/bangalore/28667869_1_cabin-crew-kolkata-ultra-long-haul-flight|title=Capt V Roopa: Flying high, and back|work=The Times of India|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nSilchar is part of the [[Silchar (Lok Sabha constituency)]]. The current member of Parliament from Silchar is Dr. [[Rajdeep Roy]] of the [[BJP]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://results.eci.gov.in/pc/en/constituencywise/ConstituencywiseS032.htm?ac=2|title=General Elections 2019|date=01/06/2019|website=Election Commission of India|access-date=01/06/2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Arun Kumar Chanda]]\n* [[Nibaran Chandra Laskar]] \n* [[Nihar Ranjan Laskar]]\n* [[Nurul Huda (CPI(M) politician)|Nurul Huda]]\n* [[Moinul Hoque Choudhury]]\n* [[Ullaskar Dutta]] \n* [[Santosh Mohan Dev]]\n* [[Kabindra Purkayastha]]\n* [[B. B. Bhattacharya]]\n* [[Sushmita Dev]]\n* [[Dilip Kumar Paul]]\n* [[Kalika Prasad Bhattacharya]]\n\n== Notable Places of Worship ==\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|width=200 | height=200\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|File:ISKCON, Ambicapatty.jpg|ISKCON, Ambicapatty\n|File:Satsang Vihar, Ambicapatty.jpg|Satsang Vihar, Ambicapatty\n|File:Ramkrishna Mission Sevashram, Jhalupara.jpg|Ramkrishna Mission Sevashram, Jhalupara\n|File:Kali Temple, Ramnagar.jpg|Kali Temple, Masimpur\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Silchar railway station]]\n* [[Silchar Airport]]\n* [[Silchar Part-X]]\n* [[Karimganj]]\n* [[Hailakandi]]\n* [[Patharkandi]]\n* [[Badarpur, Assam|Badarpur]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Silchar}}\n*[https://www.britannica.com/place/Silchar|Encyclopedia Britannica article on Silchar]\n\n{{Assam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Cachar district]]\n[[Category:Silchar| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=September 2017}} \n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement      <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n| name                            = Silchar\n| other_name                      = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = [[Municipality]] and District Headquarters\n| image_skyline                   = Silchar_barak.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Aerial view of the Barak river, Silchar\n| nickname                        = The Island of Peace and The City of Love\n| pushpin_map                     = India Assam#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = left\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Assam, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|24.82|N|92.8|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Assam]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Cachar]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Barak Valley]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| founder                         = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = Silchar Municipal Board\n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 22\n| population_total                = 1,72,830\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1              = \n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 788001 to 788032 and 788118\n| area_code                       = +91 (0) 3842\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-AS]]\n| registration_plate              = AS-11\n| website                         = {{URL|www.cachar.nic.in}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| leader_title2                   = No. of Wards\n| leader_name2                    = 30\n| leader_title3                   = Chairman\n| leader_name3                    = \n| blank_name_sec2                 = {{nowrap|[[Official languages]]}}\n| blank_info_sec2                 = [[Bengali language|Bangla]]\n| blank1_name_sec2                = Most spoken language\n| blank1_info_sec2                = [[Sylheti]]\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Silchar''' is the headquarters of [[Cachar district]] in the state of [[Assam]] in [[India]]. It is {{convert|343|km|mi|0}} south east of [[Guwahati]].\n\nIt earned it the ''bon mot'' of \u201cIsland of Peace\u201d from India's then prime minister [[Indira Gandhi]].<ref name=\"sentinel6june\">{{cite news|title=APCC member for nomination of Gaurav Gogoi from Barak Valley|url=http://www.sentinelassam.com/cachar/story.php?sec=2&subsec=12&id=120156&dtP=2012-06-07&ppr=1|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=The Sentinel, Assam|date=6 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nDuring the British rule, ships were docked at the bank of the river [[Barak river|Barak]]. Gradually, a market developed at the bank and became a major place of economic activity. The bank was covered with stones to help dock ships and vessels, and the market was developed at a place that was fully covered with stones. People started to refer to the place as ''Shiler Chor'', meaning \"a bank of stones\". With the passage of time, ''Shiler Chor'' was simplified to ''Silchar'', and ultimately the British officials started to use the name ''Silchar'' in their official documents referring to the surrounding area of the market. Thus Silchar became the official name of the place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/544040/Silchar |title=Silchar (India) - Britannica Online Encyclopedia|publisher=Britannica.com |date=|accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> Sonu(Composer)\n\n==History==\n===Cachar district records===\nIn the 1850s, [[British East India Company|British]] tea planters re-discovered the game [[polo]] in [[Manipur]] on the Burmese border with India. The first polo club in the world was formed at Silchar.<ref name=\"guardspoloclub\">{{cite web|title=The Sport|url=http://www.guardspoloclub.com/the-club/the-sport|website=guardspoloclub|accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"avictorian\">{{cite web|title=Polo of Victorians|url=http://www.avictorian.com/polo_gallery.html|website=Polo of Victorians|publisher=avictorian.com|accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first competitive modern form of polo was played in Silchar, and the plaque for this feat still stands behind the District Library, Silchar.<ref name=\"guardspoloclub\" /><ref name=\"avictorian\" />\n\n===Language Movement in Barak Valley===\n{{main|Bengali Language Movement (Barak Valley)}}\n\n[[File:Silchar Language Marters.jpeg|thumb|right|250px|[[Silchar railway station]] is described as Bhasa Shahid Station.]]\nSilchar saw one of the uprisings in favour of the [[Bengali language]]. When the Assam government, under Chief Minister [[Bimala Prasad Chaliha]], passed a circular to make [[Assamese language|Assamese]] mandatory, Bengalis of Barak Valley protested. On 19 May 1961, Assam police opened fire on unarmed protesters at [[Silchar railway station]]. Eleven people(listed below) were killed. \n* [[Kanailal Niyogi]]\n* Chandicharan Sutradhar\n* Hitesh Biswas\n* Satyendra Deb\n* Kumud Ranjan Das\n* Sunil Sarkar\n* Tarani Debnath\n* [[Sachindra Chandra Pal]]\n* [[Birendra Sutradhar]]\n* Sukamal Purakayastha\n* [[Kamala Bhattacharya]]\nAfter the popular revolt, the Assam government had to withdraw the circular and Bengali was ultimately given official status in the three districts of Barak Valley.<ref name=\"tt27dec\">{{cite news|title=No alliance with BJP, says AGP chief|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1031227/asp/northeast/story_2721710.asp|accessdate=3 March 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph, Calcutta|date=27 December 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"toi9jun\">{{cite news|title=Silchar rly station to be renamed soon|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Silchar-rly-station-to-be-renamed-soon/articleshow/4633120.cms?referral=PM|accessdate=3 March 2014|newspaper=The Times of India|date=9 Jun 2009}}</ref> Section 5 of Assam Act XVIII, 1961, safeguards the use of Bengali in the Cachar district. It says, \u201cWithout prejudice to the provisions contained in Section 3, the Bengali language shall be used for administrative and other official purposes up to and including district level.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://silcharnews.wordpress.com/2013/07/24/compulsory-use-of-bengali-language-in-cachar/|title=Compulsory use of Bengali Language in Cachar|date=2013-07-24|website=Silchar News|access-date=2016-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==Industries==\n*[[ONGC]] has its base located at [[Srikona]], near Silchar, which is known as Cachar Forward Base with ongoing operations in Tripura, Mizoram and Barak Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ongcindia.com/wps/wcm/connect/ongcindia/Home/Contact_Us/ONGC_Offices/|title=ONGC :: ONGC Offices|publisher=|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n*Cachar Paper Mill (CPM) is the only major industrial undertaking in south Assam and the adjoining states of Mizoram, Meghalaya and Tripura. Despite lack of infrastructural facilities in a remote location, CPM has a continuous record of steady improvement. During the year 2006-07, the mill recorded the highest annual production of 1,03,155 MT registering over 103% capacity utilization, which was 100% during the previous year.<ref>http://www.hindpaper.in/mills/cachar.htm</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Administration ==\nThe first municipal activities in Silchar was in 1833. It had a station committee which had nominated members. The city had its first municipality in 1893.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.asdma.gov.in/pdf/Silchar%20city%20DM%20plan.pdf|title=Disaster Management Plan|website=Assam State Disaster Management Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4th April, 2020}}</ref> Presently, it is governed by the Silchar Municipal Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.assamtribune.com/scripts/detailsnew.asp?id=jul2216/state050|title=New website of Silchar Municipal Board launched|website=The Assam Tribune Online|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSilchar is located in the southernmost part of Assam.<ref name=wikimapia>{{cite web|title=Location of Silchar|url=http://www.wikimapia.org/#lat=24.830052&lon=92.769928&z=13&l=0&m=a&v=2|work=Wikimapia Foundation|publisher=Wikimapia|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=falling1>{{cite web|title=Silchar, India Page|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/03/Silchar.html|work=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc.|publisher=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc.|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> It is located between longitudes 92\u00ba24\u2019 E and 93\u00ba15\u2019 E and latitudes 24\u00ba22\u2019N and 25\u00ba8\u2019N East and 35 meters above mean sea level.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to 2011 India [[census]], Silchar municipal area has a population of 1,72,830.<ref name=\"cen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=337446|title=Census of India 2011|last=|first=|date=|work=Govt. of India|publisher=Government of India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-01-16}}</ref> The sex ratio of Silchar is 989 females per 1,000 males, which is above the national ratio of 940 females per 1,000 males.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/india/Final_PPT_2011_chapter5.pdf|title=Census of India 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Silchar municipal area has an average literacy rate of 82.33%, higher than the national average of 74.04%, with male literacy at 84.15% and female literacy at 80.49%.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=337446|title=Census of India 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/data_files/india/Final_PPT_2011_chapter6.pdf|title=Census of India 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census2011.co.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> \n\n== Religion ==\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Silchar (2011)\n|label1 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value1 = 86.31\n|color1 = Orange\n|label2 = [[Islam]]\n|value2 = 12.17\n|color2 = Green\n|label3 = [[Jainism]]\n|value3 = 0.79\n|color3 = Red\n|label4 = [[Christianity]]\n|value4 = 0.59\n|color4 = Blue\n|label5 = [[Sikhism]]\n|value5 = 0.04\n|color5 = Yellow\n|label6 = [[Buddhism]]\n|value6 = 0.02\n|color6 = Pink\n}}\n[[Hinduism]] is the majority religion in Silchar city with around ''1,54,381'' followers. [[Islam]] is the second most popular religion in Silchar with approximately ''21,759'' followers. [[Jainism]] is followed by ''1,408'' peoples, [[Christianity]] by ''1,052'' peoples, [[Sikhism]] by ''77'' peoples and [[Buddhism]] by ''39'' peoples of Silchar city. Around ''145'' peoples didn't stated their religion.<ref>[https://indiapopulation2019.com/population-of-silchar-2019.html Silchar Religion Data census 2011]</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\nSilchar has a borderline [[tropical monsoon climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Am'') slightly too hot in the \u201cwinter\u201d or \u201ccool\u201d season to qualify as a [[humid subtropical climate]] (''Cwa''). During this \u201ccool\u201d season the weather is generally warm and dry with cool to mild mornings; however, the \u201cwet\u201d season begins early as [[Monsoon of South Asia|the monsoon]] moves into the region during April, with the result that for seven months of the year Silchar has very hot and humid weather with heavy thunderstorms almost every afternoon until the middle of October, when there is usually a brief period of hot and relatively dry weather before the \u201ccool\u201d season sets in during November.\n{{Weather box\n|location = Silchar (1981\u20132010, extremes 1901\u2013present)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|temperature colour = \n| Jan record high C = 31.0\n| Feb record high C = 35.0\n| Mar record high C = 37.8\n| Apr record high C = 39.4\n| May record high C = 39.1\n| Jun record high C = 37.9\n| Jul record high C = 39.4\n| Aug record high C = 39.0\n| Sep record high C = 38.3\n| Oct record high C = 36.7\n| Nov record high C = 35.0\n| Dec record high C = 31.7\n|year record high C = 39.4\n| Jan high C = 25.3\n| Feb high C = 27.6\n| Mar high C = 30.4\n| Apr high C = 31.0\n| May high C = 31.6\n| Jun high C = 32.1\n| Jul high C = 32.2\n| Aug high C = 32.7\n| Sep high C = 32.3\n| Oct high C = 31.6\n| Nov high C = 29.6\n| Dec high C = 26.7\n| year high C = 30.3\n| Jan mean C = 19.0\n| Feb mean C = 20.8\n| Mar mean C = 24.6\n| Apr mean C = 26.7\n| May mean C = 27.7\n| Jun mean C = 28.5\n| Jul mean C = 28.9\n| Aug mean C = 29.2\n| Sep mean C = 29.0\n| Oct mean C = 27.5\n| Nov mean C = 24.4\n| Dec mean C = 20.6\n|year mean C = 25.6\n| Jan low C = 12.2\n| Feb low C = 14.2\n| Mar low C = 17.9\n| Apr low C = 21.1\n| May low C = 23.1\n| Jun low C = 24.9\n| Jul low C = 25.3\n| Aug low C = 25.4\n| Sep low C = 25.0\n| Oct low C = 23.0\n| Nov low C = 18.6\n| 