{"title_page": "Brit shalom (naming ceremony)", "text_new": "{{short description|Naming ceremony for newborn Jewish boys that does not involve circumcision}}\n'''Brit shalom''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05e9\u05dc\u05d5\u05dd}} (\"covenant of peace\"), also called '''alternative brit''' (or bris in Yiddish and Ashkenazi Hebrew), '''brit ben''', '''brit chayim''' or '''brit tikkun''', is a [[naming ceremony]] for newborn [[Judaism|Jewish]] boys that does not involve [[circumcision]]. It is intended to replace the traditional [[brit milah]], and is promoted by groups such as Beyond the Bris and Jews Against Circumcision. The term is generally not used for girls, since [[Zeved habat|their naming ceremony]] does not involve circumcision.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nBrit shalom is recognized by organizations affiliated with [[Humanistic Judaism]] like the [[Society for Humanistic Judaism]], The Congress of Secular Jewish Organizations, and the [[International Institute for Secular Humanistic Judaism]], but not by any of the major denominations in Judaism.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} The Reform movement rabbis welcome these families in their community, although not all of them advertise this in public.<ref name=\"JWeekly\">{{Cite news|last=Silvers|first=Emma|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2012/01/06/alternative-ritual-sans-snip-catching-on-in-bay-area/|title=Brit shalom is catching on, for parents who dont want to circumcise their child|date=6 January 2012|work=[[JWeekly]]|location=[[San Francisco]]|access-date=4 January 2020}}; {{Cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2014/02/14/choosing-not-to-circumcise-last-frontier-of-jewish-inclusion/|title=Choosing not to circumcise last frontier of Jewish inclusion|date=14 February 2014|work=JWeekly|location=San Francisco|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Religious male circumcision#Opposition within Judaism}}\n\nThe first Brit shalom ceremony was celebrated by Rabbi [[Sherwin Wine]], the founder of the [[Society for Humanistic Judaism]], around 1970.<ref name=\"Lowenfeld2011\">{{cite news |last=Lowenfeld |first=Jonah |date=2 August 2011 |title=Little-known non-cutting ritual appeals to some who oppose circumcision |url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/los_angeles/community/94746/ |work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]] |location=[[Los Angeles|LA]] |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ceremony==\nThere are different forms of brit shalom ceremonies. Some of them involve the [[Foot washing|washing of the baby's feet]], called ''[[Brit rechitzah]]''.<ref>[http://www.circumstitions.com/Jewish.html#ceremonies Brit Shalom/Shalem/Milim: Covenant of Peace/Wholeness/Words]</ref> Brit shalom ceremonies are performed by a [[rabbi]] or a lay person; in this context, ''rabbi'' does not necessarily imply belief in God, as some celebrants belong to Humanistic Judaism.<ref name=\"SHJ\">{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |url=https://iishj.org/lcshj/lcshj-resolutions/ |title=LCSHJ Resolutions: Circumcision and Jewish Identity |date=April 2002 |website=[[International Institute for Secular Humanistic Judaism]] |publisher=[[Society for Humanistic Judaism]] |location=[[Farmington Hills, Michigan]] |access-date=11 March 2020}}; {{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |url=https://shj.org/humanistic-jewish-life/life-cycles/birth-celebrations/ |title=Birth Celebrations |date=2016 |website=[[Society for Humanistic Judaism]] |location=Farmington Hills, Michigan |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\nThe actual number of brit shalom ceremonies performed per year is not known. Filmmaker Eli Ungar-Sargon, who is opposed to circumcision, said regarding its current popularity \u2033Calling it a marginal phenomenon would be generous\u2033.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} This was confirmed by a survey conducted by ''[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|The Jewish Journal]]'' among mohalim and brit shalom celebrants in the Los Angeles area.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} However, according to ''[[The New York Times]]'' and [[NPR]], its popularity is increasing.<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref name=\"Lowenfeld2011\" />\n\nA growing number<ref name=\"chernikoff\">{{Cite news\n |url         = https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN22970720071003?pageNumber=1\n |title       = Jewish \"intactivists\" in U.S. stop circumcising\n |access-date=4 January 2020\n |last        = Chernikoff\n |first       = Helen\n |date        = October 3, 2007\n |newspaper   = [[Reuters]]\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081227025338/http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN22970720071003?pageNumber=1\n |archivedate = December 27, 2008\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Schonfeld\">{{cite web |url=https://www.circinfo.org/Jews_against_circumcision.html |title=Jewish voices against circumcision getting stronger |last=Schoenfeld |first=Victor |date=2014 |website=Circinfo.org |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kasher\">{{cite news\n |last        = Kasher\n |first       = Rani\n |title       = It's 2017. Time to Talk About Circumcision\n |newspaper   = [[Haaretz]]\n |location    = [[Tel Aviv]]\n |language    = English\n |date        = 23 August 2017\n |url         = http://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-1.808557\n |access-date=4 January 2020\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170904032317/http://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-1.808557\n |archivedate = 4 September 2017\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Jewish News\">{{cite news |last=Oryszczuk |first=Stephen |date=28 February 2018 |title=The Jewish parents cutting out the bris |url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/the-jewish-parents-cutting-out-the-bris/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location=[[Jerusalem]] |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> of contemporary Jews and [[Intactivist]] Jewish groups in the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], and [[Israel]], both religious and secular, choose not to circumcise their sons.<ref name=\"chernikoff\" /><ref name=\"Schonfeld\" /><ref name=\"kasher\" /><ref name=\"Jewish News\" /><ref name=\"Goldman 1997\">{{cite web |url=http://jewishcircumcision.org/spectator.htm |title=Circumcision: A Source of Jewish Pain |last=Goldman |first=Ronald |date=1997 |website=Jewish Circumcision Resource Center |publisher=Jewish Spectator |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Kimmel\">{{Cite journal |last=Kimmel |first=Michael S. |author-link=Michael Kimmel |title=The Kindest Un-Cut: Feminism, Judaism, and My Son's Foreskin |url=http://www.cirp.org/pages/cultural/kimmel1/ |journal=[[Tikkun (magazine)|Tikkun]] |volume=16 |issue=3 |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |pages=43\u201348 |date=May\u2013June 2001 |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> Among the reasons for their choice, Intactivist Jewish parents state that circumcision is a form of [[child abuse]] that involves [[genital mutilation]] [[Forced circumcision|forced on men]] and [[violence]] against helpless infants,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\">{{cite journal |last=Goodman |first=Jason |url=http://www.cirp.org/library/cultural/goodman1999/ |title=Jewish circumcision: an alternative perspective |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=1999 |journal=[[BJU International]] |volume=83 |issue=Supplement 1 |publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]] |pages=22-27 |doi=10.1046/j.1464-410x.1999.0830s1022.x |pmid=10349411}}</ref> a violation of [[children's rights]],<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Schonfeld\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> and their opinion that circumcision is a dangerous,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> unnecessary,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> painful,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> [[Psychological trauma|traumatic]] and [[Psychological stress|stressful]] event for the child,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> which can cause even further psychophysical complications down the road, including serious [[disability]] and even death.<ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Boyle |first1=Gregory J. |last2=Svoboda |first2=J. Steven |last3=Price |first3=Christopher P. |last4=Turner |first4=J. Neville |date=2000 |title=Circumcision of Healthy Boys: Criminal Assault? |url=http://www.cirp.org/library/legal/boyle1/ |journal=Journal of Law and Medicine |volume=7 |issue= |pages=301\u2013310 |doi= |access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref> They are assisted in the celebration of brit shalom by a small number of [[Reform Judaism|Reform]], [[Liberal Judaism (United Kingdom)|Liberal]], and [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]] rabbis,<ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Schonfeld\" /><ref name=\"Jewish News\" /> and also by Humanistic Jewish congregations.<ref>{{cite web\n  | url      = http://www.circumstitions.com/Jewish-shalom.html\n  | title      = Celebrants of Brit Shalom\n  | accessdate      = 2007-10-03\n  | last      = Reiss, MD\n  | first      = Dr. Mark\n  | year      = 2006\n  | publisher      = Brit Shalom\n  | url-status      = dead\n  | archiveurl      = https://web.archive.org/web/20141213065752/http://www.circumstitions.com/Jewish-shalom.html\n  | archivedate      = 2014-12-13\n  }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | url      = http://www.jewsagainstcircumcision.org/brisshalom.htm\n  | title      = Providers of Brit Shalom\n  | accessdate      = 2007-10-03\n  | last      = Goldman, PhD\n  | first      = Ron\n  | year      = 2006\n  | publisher      = [[Jews Against Circumcision]]\n  | url-status      = dead\n  | archiveurl      = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929080506/http://www.jewsagainstcircumcision.org/brisshalom.htm\n  | archivedate      = 2007-09-29\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Recognition== \nRitual circumcision of a male child on the eighth day of life is part of [[Jewish law]].<ref name = \"Greenberg\">{{Citation\n | last =Greenberg\n | first =Zoe\n | author-link =\n | author2-link =\n | title =When Jewish Parents Decide Not to Circumcise\n | newspaper =New York Times\n | pages =\n \n | date =25 July 2017\n | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/25/well/family/cutting-out-the-bris.html\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date =13 September 2017}}</ref> Although one does not need to be circumcised to be Jewish,<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/4391-circumcision |title=Circumcision |last1=Kohler |first1=Kaufmann |last2=Hirsch |first2=Emil G. |last3=Jacobs |first3=Joseph |last4=Friedenwald |first4=Aaron |last5=Broyd\u00e9 |first5=Isaac |author1-link=Kaufmann Kohler |author2-link=Emil G. Hirsch |author3-link=Joseph Jacobs |author5-link=Isaac Broyd\u00e9 |publisher=[[Kopelman Foundation]] |website=[[Jewish Encyclopedia]] |date=1906 |access-date=4 January 2020 |quote=Unlike Christian [[baptism]], circumcision, however important it may be, is not a sacrament which gives the Jew his religious character as a Jew. An uncircumcised Jew is a full Jew by birth (\u1e24ul. 4b; 'Ab. Zarah 27a; Shul\u1e25an 'Aruk, Yoreh De'ah, 264, 1). [...] In 1847 [[David Einhorn (rabbi)|Einhorn]], as chief rabbi of Mecklenburg, became involved in a controversy with Franz Delitzsch of Rostock, who denounced him for acting contrary to Jewish law in naming and consecrating an uncircumcised child in the synagogue. Einhorn, in an \"opinion\" published a second time in his \"Sinai\", 1857, pp. 736 et seq., declared, with references to [[Rabbinic literature|ancient and modern rabbinical authorities]], that a child of Jewish parents was a Jew even if uncircumcised, and retained all the privileges, as well as all the obligations, of a Jew. This view he also expressed in his catechism, his prayer-book, and his sermons, emphasizing the spiritual character of the [[Abrahamic covenant]]\u2014\"the seal of Abraham placed upon the spirit of Israel as God's covenant people.\"}}</ref> [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jews]] consider an intended failure to follow this commandment as bringing forth the penalty of ''[[kareth]]'', or being \"cut off\" from the community, as well as being indicative of a conscious decision to cut oneself off from one's people. However, even in the most Orthodox groups, Jewish identity is defined by [[Matrilineality in Judaism|matrilineal descent]];<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /> a child born to a Jewish mother is recognized as Jewish, regardless of the status of the genitals.<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> In Progressive Judaism, intact boys are usually accepted for religious training and [[bar mitzvah]] if they are sons of a Jewish mother and have been raised with a Jewish identity.<ref name = \"Greenberg\" /> Movements that do not see Jewish law as binding, such as Reform Judaism and Humanistic Judaism, may allow this ceremony.<ref name=\"SHJ\" /><ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref name = \"Greenberg\" />\n\nSome rabbis welcome uncircumcised boys in their congregations, but not all of them advertise this publicly.<ref name=\"JWeekly\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bodily integrity]]\n* [[Children's rights]]\n* [[Circumcision controversies]]\n* [[Ethics of circumcision]]\n* [[Religious male circumcision]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Circumcision debate]]\n[[Category:Humanistic Judaism]]\n[[Category:Reconstructionist Judaism]]\n[[Category:Reform Judaism]]\n[[Category:Judaism and children]]\n[[Category:Birth in Judaism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Naming ceremony for newborn Jewish boys that does not involve circumcision}}\n'''Brit shalom''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05e9\u05dc\u05d5\u05dd}} (\"covenant of peace\"), also called '''alternative brit''' (or bris in Yiddish and Ashkenazi Hebrew), '''brit ben''', '''brit chayim''' or '''brit tikkun''', is a [[naming ceremony]] for newborn [[Judaism|Jewish]] boys that does not involve [[circumcision]]. It is intended to replace the traditional [[brit milah]], and is promoted by groups such as Beyond the Bris and Jews Against Circumcision. The term is generally not used for girls, since [[Zeved habat|their naming ceremony]] does not involve circumcision.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nBrit shalom is recognized by organizations affiliated with [[Humanistic Judaism]] like the [[Society for Humanistic Judaism]], The Congress of Secular Jewish Organizations, and the [[International Institute for Secular Humanistic Judaism]], but not by any of the major denominations in Judaism.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} The Reform movement rabbis welcome these families in their community, although not all of them advertise this in public.<ref name=\"JWeekly\">{{Cite news|last=Silvers|first=Emma|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2012/01/06/alternative-ritual-sans-snip-catching-on-in-bay-area/|title=Brit shalom is catching on, for parents who dont want to circumcise their child|date=6 January 2012|work=[[JWeekly]]|location=[[San Francisco]]|access-date=4 January 2020}}; {{Cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2014/02/14/choosing-not-to-circumcise-last-frontier-of-jewish-inclusion/|title=Choosing not to circumcise last frontier of Jewish inclusion|date=14 February 2014|work=JWeekly|location=San Francisco|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Religious male circumcision#Opposition within Judaism}}\n\nThe first Brit shalom ceremony was celebrated by Rabbi [[Sherwin Wine]], the founder of the [[Society for Humanistic Judaism]], around 1970.<ref name=\"Lowenfeld2011\">{{cite news |last=Lowenfeld |first=Jonah |date=2 August 2011 |title=Little-known non-cutting ritual appeals to some who oppose circumcision |url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/los_angeles/community/94746/ |work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]] |location=[[Los Angeles]] |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ceremony==\nThere are different forms of brit shalom ceremonies. Some of them involve the [[Foot washing|washing of the baby's feet]], called ''[[Brit rechitzah]]''.<ref>[http://www.circumstitions.com/Jewish.html#ceremonies Brit Shalom/Shalem/Milim: Covenant of Peace/Wholeness/Words]</ref> Brit shalom ceremonies are performed by a [[rabbi]] or a lay person; in this context, ''rabbi'' does not necessarily imply belief in God, as some celebrants belong to Humanistic Judaism.<ref name=\"SHJ\">{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |url=https://iishj.org/lcshj/lcshj-resolutions/ |title=LCSHJ Resolutions: Circumcision and Jewish Identity |date=April 2002 |website=[[International Institute for Secular Humanistic Judaism]] |publisher=[[Society for Humanistic Judaism]] |location=[[Farmington Hills, Michigan]] |access-date=11 March 2020}}; {{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |url=https://shj.org/humanistic-jewish-life/life-cycles/birth-celebrations/ |title=Birth Celebrations |date=2016 |website=[[Society for Humanistic Judaism]] |location=Farmington Hills, Michigan |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\nThe actual number of brit shalom ceremonies performed per year is not known. Filmmaker Eli Ungar-Sargon, who is opposed to circumcision, said regarding its current popularity \u2033Calling it a marginal phenomenon would be generous\u2033.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} This was confirmed by a survey conducted by ''[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|The Jewish Journal]]'' among mohalim and brit shalom celebrants in the Los Angeles area.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} However, according to ''[[The New York Times]]'' and [[NPR]], its popularity is increasing.<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref name=\"Lowenfeld2011\" />\n\nA growing number<ref name=\"chernikoff\">{{Cite news\n |url         = https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN22970720071003?pageNumber=1\n |title       = Jewish \"intactivists\" in U.S. stop circumcising\n |access-date=4 January 2020\n |last        = Chernikoff\n |first       = Helen\n |date        = October 3, 2007\n |newspaper   = [[Reuters]]\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081227025338/http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN22970720071003?pageNumber=1\n |archivedate = December 27, 2008\n}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Schonfeld\">{{cite web |url=https://www.circinfo.org/Jews_against_circumcision.html |title=Jewish voices against circumcision getting stronger |last=Schoenfeld |first=Victor |date=2014 |website=Circinfo.org |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kasher\">{{cite news\n |last        = Kasher\n |first       = Rani\n |title       = It's 2017. Time to Talk About Circumcision\n |newspaper   = [[Haaretz]]\n |location    = [[Tel Aviv]]\n |language    = English\n |date        = 23 August 2017\n |url         = http://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-1.808557\n |access-date=4 January 2020\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170904032317/http://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-1.808557\n |archivedate = 4 September 2017\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Jewish News\">{{cite news |last=Oryszczuk |first=Stephen |date=28 February 2018 |title=The Jewish parents cutting out the bris |url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/the-jewish-parents-cutting-out-the-bris/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location=[[Jerusalem]] |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> of contemporary Jews and [[Intactivist]] Jewish groups in the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], and [[Israel]], both religious and secular, choose not to circumcise their sons.<ref name=\"chernikoff\" /><ref name=\"Schonfeld\" /><ref name=\"kasher\" /><ref name=\"Jewish News\" /><ref name=\"Goldman 1997\">{{cite web |url=http://jewishcircumcision.org/spectator.htm |title=Circumcision: A Source of Jewish Pain |last=Goldman |first=Ronald |date=1997 |website=Jewish Circumcision Resource Center |publisher=Jewish Spectator |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Kimmel\">{{Cite journal |last=Kimmel |first=Michael S. |author-link=Michael Kimmel |title=The Kindest Un-Cut: Feminism, Judaism, and My Son's Foreskin |url=http://www.cirp.org/pages/cultural/kimmel1/ |journal=[[Tikkun (magazine)|Tikkun]] |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=43\u201348 |date=May\u2013June 2001 |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> Among the reasons for their choice, Intactivist Jewish parents state that circumcision is a form of [[child abuse]] that involves [[genital mutilation]] [[Forced circumcision|forced on men]] and [[violence]] against helpless infants,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\">{{cite journal |last=Goodman |first=Jason |url=http://www.cirp.org/library/cultural/goodman1999/ |title=Jewish circumcision: an alternative perspective |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=1999 |journal=[[BJU International]] |volume=83 |issue=Supplement 1 |pages=22-27 |doi=10.1046/j.1464-410x.1999.0830s1022.x |pmid=10349411}}</ref> a violation of [[children's rights]],<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Schonfeld\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> and their opinion that circumcision is a dangerous,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> unnecessary,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> painful,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> [[Psychological trauma|traumatic]] and [[Psychological stress|stressful]] event for the child,<ref name=\"Goldman 1997\" /><ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> which can cause even further psychophysical complications down the road, including serious [[disability]] and even death.<ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Boyle |first1=Gregory J. |last2=Svoboda |first2=J. Steven |last3=Price |first3=Christopher P. |last4=Turner |first4=J. Neville |date=2000 |title=Circumcision of Healthy Boys: Criminal Assault? |url=http://www.cirp.org/library/legal/boyle1/ |journal=Journal of Law and Medicine |volume=7 |issue= |pages=301\u2013310 |doi= |access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref> They are assisted in the celebration of brit shalom by a small number of [[Reform Judaism|Reform]], [[Liberal Judaism (United Kingdom)|Liberal]], and [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]] rabbis,<ref name=\"Kimmel\" /><ref name=\"Schonfeld\" /><ref name=\"Jewish News\" /> and also by Humanistic Jewish congregations.<ref>{{cite web\n  | url      = http://www.circumstitions.com/Jewish-shalom.html\n  | title      = Celebrants of Brit Shalom\n  | accessdate      = 2007-10-03\n  | last      = Reiss, MD\n  | first      = Dr. Mark\n  | year      = 2006\n  | publisher      = Brit Shalom\n  | url-status      = dead\n  | archiveurl      = https://web.archive.org/web/20141213065752/http://www.circumstitions.com/Jewish-shalom.html\n  | archivedate      = 2014-12-13\n  }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | url      = http://www.jewsagainstcircumcision.org/brisshalom.htm\n  | title      = Providers of Brit Shalom\n  | accessdate      = 2007-10-03\n  | last      = Goldman, PhD\n  | first      = Ron\n  | year      = 2006\n  | publisher      = [[Jews Against Circumcision]]\n  | url-status      = dead\n  | archiveurl      = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929080506/http://www.jewsagainstcircumcision.org/brisshalom.htm\n  | archivedate      = 2007-09-29\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Recognition== \nRitual circumcision of a male child on the eighth day of life is part of [[Jewish law]].<ref name = \"Greenberg\">{{Citation\n | last =Greenberg\n | first =Zoe\n | author-link =\n | author2-link =\n | title =When Jewish Parents Decide Not to Circumcise\n | newspaper =New York Times\n | pages =\n \n | date =25 July 2017\n | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/25/well/family/cutting-out-the-bris.html\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date =13 September 2017}}</ref> Although one does not need to be circumcised to be Jewish,<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/4391-circumcision |title=Circumcision |last1=Kohler |first1=Kaufmann |last2=Hirsch |first2=Emil G. |last3=Jacobs |first3=Joseph |last4=Friedenwald |first4=Aaron |last5=Broyd\u00e9 |first5=Isaac |author1-link=Kaufmann Kohler |author2-link=Emil G. Hirsch |author3-link=Joseph Jacobs |author5-link=Isaac Broyd\u00e9 |publisher=[[Kopelman Foundation]] |website=[[Jewish Encyclopedia]] |date=1906 |access-date=4 January 2020 |quote=Unlike Christian [[baptism]], circumcision, however important it may be, is not a sacrament which gives the Jew his religious character as a Jew. An uncircumcised Jew is a full Jew by birth (\u1e24ul. 4b; 'Ab. Zarah 27a; Shul\u1e25an 'Aruk, Yoreh De'ah, 264, 1). [...] In 1847 [[David Einhorn (rabbi)|Einhorn]], as chief rabbi of Mecklenburg, became involved in a controversy with Franz Delitzsch of Rostock, who denounced him for acting contrary to Jewish law in naming and consecrating an uncircumcised child in the synagogue. Einhorn, in an \"opinion\" published a second time in his \"Sinai\", 1857, pp. 736 et seq., declared, with references to [[Rabbinic literature|ancient and modern rabbinical authorities]], that a child of Jewish parents was a Jew even if uncircumcised, and retained all the privileges, as well as all the obligations, of a Jew. This view he also expressed in his catechism, his prayer-book, and his sermons, emphasizing the spiritual character of the [[Abrahamic covenant]]\u2014\"the seal of Abraham placed upon the spirit of Israel as God's covenant people.\"}}</ref> [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jews]] consider an intended failure to follow this commandment as bringing forth the penalty of ''[[kareth]]'', or being \"cut off\" from the community, as well as being indicative of a conscious decision to cut oneself off from one's people. However, even in the most Orthodox groups, Jewish identity is defined by [[Matrilineality in Judaism|matrilineal descent]];<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /> a child born to a Jewish mother is recognized as Jewish, regardless of the status of the genitals.<ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref name=\"Goodman 1999\" /> In Progressive Judaism, intact boys are usually accepted for religious training and [[bar mitzvah]] if they are sons of a Jewish mother and have been raised with a Jewish identity.<ref name = \"Greenberg\" /> Movements that do not see Jewish law as binding, such as Reform Judaism and Humanistic Judaism, may allow this ceremony.<ref name=\"SHJ\" /><ref name=\"JWeekly\" /><ref name = \"Greenberg\" />\n\nSome rabbis welcome uncircumcised boys in their congregations, but not all of them advertise this publicly.<ref name=\"JWeekly\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bodily integrity]]\n* [[Children's rights]]\n* [[Circumcision controversies]]\n* [[Ethics of circumcision]]\n* [[Religious male circumcision]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Circumcision debate]]\n[[Category:Humanistic Judaism]]\n[[Category:Reconstructionist Judaism]]\n[[Category:Reform Judaism]]\n[[Category:Judaism and children]]\n[[Category:Birth in Judaism]]\n", "name_user": "GenoV84", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added publishers to 2 refs.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brit_shalom_(naming_ceremony)"}
{"title_page": "Alf Kumalo", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n'''Alfred Khumalo<ref>{{cite web|last=Alf|first=Kumalo|title=Alf Kumalo book|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/Alf-Kumalo/303458980467|work=Alf Kumalo|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> ''' (5 September 1930{{spaced ndash}}21 October 2012),<ref name=Weber>{{cite news|last=Weber|first=Bruce|title=Alf Kumalo, Whose Photography Indicted Apartheid, Dies at 82|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/world/africa/alf-kumalo-south-african-photographer-of-apartheid-dies-at-82.html?hpw|accessdate=15 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 November 2012}}</ref> better known as '''Alf Kumalo''', and with the surname sometimes spelled '''Khumalo''', was a South African documentary photographer and [[photojournalist]].<ref name=Weber /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/8a142f004d2ade62840af5e570eb4ca2/SA-mourns-death-of-Alf-Khumalo-20122210|title=SA mourns death of Alf Khumalo|publisher=sabc.co.za|accessdate=22 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002181018/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/8a142f004d2ade62840af5e570eb4ca2/SA-mourns-death-of-Alf-Khumalo-20122210|archive-date=2 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n\nAlf Kumalo was born in [[Utrecht, KwaZulu-Natal|Utrecht]] near Newcastle in the province of [[KwaZulu-Natal]].<ref>http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/alfred-khumalo</ref> He first worked in a garage doing various jobs and then started freelancing for various publications, selling his photographs where he could. He did a lot of work for the ''[[The Bantu World|Bantu World]]''.\n\nIn 1956, he found a permanent position at the ''[[Golden City Post]]'' and later received assignments from ''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', a South African daily, ''[[Drum (South African magazine)|Drum]]'' magazine, and international publications like ''[[The New York Times]]''. He was among the photographers who captured the [[Sharpeville massacre]] on 21 March 1960.<ref name=Weber />\n\nIn 1963, while working for ''Drum'', he was selected together with Harry Mashabela to go and shoot a story about African students in the [[Iron Curtain]] countries. The two made the front cover of the next edition of the magazine, \"''Drum'' men go to Europe\".\n\nWhile in London, he interviewed [[Cassius Clay]] and then found out that he had won first place in a photographic competition. The prize was an [[Austin Cambridge]] motor car.<ref name='50 years'>{{cite news |title=Alf Kumalo celebrates 50 years in journalism |publisher=mediaweb |url=http://www.mediaweb.co.za/mnews_j_.asp?id=2854 |work=mediaweb |accessdate=21 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928154244/http://www.mediaweb.co.za/mnews_j_.asp?id=2854 |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Kumalo had been encouraged to enter by David Hazelhurst, the editor of ''Drum''.\n\nKumalo had used his African names ''Mangaliso Dukuza'' because he wanted the judging to be impartial and not influenced by his reputation. A picture of him and his award was published by the ''Star'' on its front page. \"A lot of black people talked about it for days afterwards, because in those days they would only get on to the front pages of white newspapers if they were thieves.\"<ref name='50 years' />\n\nDespite the prospect of being arrested and assaulted, Kumalo kept on taking pictures, sometimes at personal cost. David Hazelhurst recalled:\n\n<blockquote>One day in 1963, when I was editor of ''Drum'' magazine, Alf Khumalo walked into my office carrying a picture. It showed a burly policeman delivering a vicious kick between the legs of reporter Harry Mashabela from behind. Such was the power of the kick you could see the shape of his boot exploding through the front of Mashabela' trousers.\n\nIt was the year of the jackboot of John Vorster, habeas corpus had disappeared, the 90-day-detention without trial Act had given policemen a license to kill and assault behind closed doors with impunity.\n\nThe police hated journalists \u2013 and photographers in particular, for their pictures portrayed the truth about an evil system, and Kumalo, despite warnings, risked a severe beating to take the Mashabela picture. He had tried to sell it to several papers with no success.<ref name='Nat Nakasa Award'>{{cite news | first= | last= | author2= | title=Veteran photographer Alf Kumalo wins the 2005 Nat Nakasa Award | date= | publisher=SA National Editors Forum | url =http://www.sanef.org.za/nat_nakasa_award/ | work = | pages = | accessdate = 17 May 2007 | language = }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHazelhurst splashed the picture across two pages of ''Drum''.\n\nOver the years Kumalo photographed and documented many of the historic moments in recent South African history. These include the [[Treason Trial]], the [[Rivonia Trial]], the emergence of [[Black Consciousness Movement|Black Consciousness]], the [[Soweto uprising|Student Uprising]] of 1976 and the [[Convention for a Democratic South Africa|Codesa]] talks. This was despite numerous periods of detention, arrests and official [[harassment]].\n\nHis work has appeared in international newspapers like ''[[The Observer]]'', ''The New York Times'', ''[[New York Post]]'', and the ''[[Sunday Independent (South Africa)|Sunday Independent]]''. Locally, he also worked for ''Drum'' magazine and the long-defunct ''[[Rand Daily Mail]]''.<ref name='5 decades'>{{cite news | first=Mandisi | last=Majavu | author2= | title=Alf Khumalo: 5 decades in photos | date=5 November 2004 | publisher=SA Information | url=http://www.southafrica.info/what_happening/news/features/khumalophotos.htm | work= | pages= | accessdate=16 May 2007 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184707/http://www.southafrica.info/what_happening/news/features/khumalophotos.htm | archive-date=30 September 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTo assist the upcoming generation of South African photographers, Kumalo opened a photographic school in [[Diepmeadow, Gauteng|Diepkloof]] [[Soweto]] in 2002.<ref name=Weber /> The school offers nine-month courses designed to train photographers from disadvantaged backgrounds.<ref name='Interview'>{{cite news | first=Izane | last=Mynhardt | author2= | title=Interview: Alfred Khumalo | date= | publisher=New Visions Africa | url =http://www.newvisionsafrica.com/files2/volume%2013/interview.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 16 May 2007 | language = }}</ref>\n\nHe died on 21 October 2012.<ref>http://www.iol.com</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n* ''Mandela: Echoes of an era'' / by Alf Kumalo; text by Es'kia Mphahlele, Penguin Books, 1990, {{ISBN|0-14-014316-5}}\n* ''Alf Kumalo: South African Photographer'', Itala Vivan & Alf Kumalo, Leonardo arte, {{ISBN|88-7813-384-1}}\n*''Through My Lens: A Photographic Memoir'', Alf Kumalo, text by Tanya Farber, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0624044673}}\n*''8115: A Prisoner's Home'', Alf Kumalo; text by Zukiswa Wanner, Penguin Books, 2010, {{ISBN|9780143538370}}\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Solo exhibitions===\n\n* 2004 \u2013 59th Session of the United Nations General Assembly in New York City \u2013 a collection of his life's work \u2013 the exhibition was much acclaimed<ref name='Interview' />\n\n===Group exhibitions===\n\n* 2001 \u2013 ''Soweto \u2013 A South African Myth'' \u2013 Photographs from the 1950s (by Alf Khumalo, [[Ernest Cole (photographer)|Ernest Cole]] and [[J\u00fcrgen Schadeberg]]). The core of the exhibition is the [[Soweto uprising|student uprising]] of 1976. This includes some of [[Peter Magubane]]'s work.\n* 2002 \u2013 ''Shooting Resistance: South African Photography 1976 \u2013 1994'' \u2013 The exhibition documented the period of upheavals that began with the student-led [[Soweto uprising]] of 1976 and culminated in the collapse of the apartheid regime and the introduction of democratic elections in 1994. Included were photographs by Alf Kumalo, [[J\u00fcrgen Schadeberg]] and [[Peter Magubane]].\n* 2006 \u2013 ''Madiba: Public and Private'' \u2013 Nelson Mandela Foundation, Johannesburg. Works by photographers Alf Kumalo and [[J\u00fcrgen Schadeberg]]. Schadeberg's photos are of the public images of [[Nelson Mandela|Mandela]] from the 1950s, during the [[Defiance Campaign]] and before Mandela's imprisonment, while Kumalo's are of Mandela's private life, particularly of his family. Many of Kumalo's pictures were taken of Mandela's growing family, to send to Mandela in jail.\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2004 \u2013 South African [[Order of Ikhamanga]] in Silver for \"his excellent contribution to documentary photography and journalism in South Africa\".<ref name='National Orders'>{{cite news| title=Alfred Khumalo| date=10 November 2004| publisher=S A Government| url=http://www.info.gov.za/aboutgovt/orders/2004/khumalo.htm| accessdate=16 May 2007| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171009/http://www.info.gov.za/aboutgovt/orders/2004/khumalo.htm| archivedate=30 September 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 [[South African National Editors' Forum|South African National Editors Forum]] \"Nat Nakasa Award for Media Integrity\" for displaying \"courageous journalism throughout his professional career\".<ref name='Nat Nakasa Award' />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kumalo, Alf}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Amajuba District Municipality]]\n[[Category:South African photographers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n'''Alfred Khumalo<ref>{{cite web|last=Alf|first=Kumalo|title=Alf Kumalo book|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/Alf-Kumalo/303458980467|work=Alf Kumalo|accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref> ''' (5 September 1930{{spaced ndash}}21 October 2012),<ref name=Weber>{{cite news|last=Weber|first=Bruce|title=Alf Kumalo, Whose Photography Indicted Apartheid, Dies at 82|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/world/africa/alf-kumalo-south-african-photographer-of-apartheid-dies-at-82.html?hpw|accessdate=15 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 November 2012}}</ref> better known as '''Alf Kumalo''', and with the surname sometimes spelled '''Khumalo''', was a South African documentary photographer and [[photojournalist]].<ref name=Weber /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/8a142f004d2ade62840af5e570eb4ca2/SA-mourns-death-of-Alf-Khumalo-20122210|title=SA mourns death of Alf Khumalo|publisher=sabc.co.za|accessdate=22 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002181018/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/8a142f004d2ade62840af5e570eb4ca2/SA-mourns-death-of-Alf-Khumalo-20122210|archive-date=2 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n\nAlf Kumalo was born in [[Utrecht, KwaZulu-Natal|Utrecht]] near Newcastle in the province of [[KwaZulu-Natal]].<ref>http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/alfred-khumalo</ref> He first worked in a garage doing various jobs and then started freelancing for various publications, selling his photographs where he could. He did a lot of work for the ''[[The Bantu World|Bantu World]]''.\n\nIn 1956, he found a permanent position at the ''[[Golden City Post]]'' and later received assignments from ''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', a South African daily, ''[[Drum (South African magazine)|Drum]]'' magazine, and international publications like ''[[The New York Times]]''. He was among the photographers who captured the [[Sharpeville massacre]] on 21 March 1960.<ref name=Weber />\n\nIn 1963, while working for ''Drum'', he was selected together with Harry Mashabela to go and shoot a story about African students in the [[Iron Curtain]] countries. The two made the front cover of the next edition of the magazine, \"''Drum'' men go to Europe\".\n\nWhile in London, he interviewed [[Cassius Clay]] and then found out that he had won first place in a photographic competition. The prize was an [[Austin Cambridge]] motor car.<ref name='50 years'>{{cite news |title=Alf Kumalo celebrates 50 years in journalism |publisher=mediaweb |url=http://www.mediaweb.co.za/mnews_j_.asp?id=2854 |work=mediaweb |accessdate=21 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928154244/http://www.mediaweb.co.za/mnews_j_.asp?id=2854 |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Kumalo had been encouraged to enter by David Hazelhurst, the editor of ''Drum''.\n\nKumalo had used his African names ''Mangaliso Dukuza'' because he wanted the judging to be impartial and not influenced by his reputation. A picture of him and his award was published by the ''Star'' on its front page. \"A lot of black people talked about it for days afterwards, because in those days they would only get on to the front pages of white newspapers if they were thieves.\"<ref name='50 years' />\n\nDespite the prospect of being arrested and assaulted, Kumalo kept on taking pictures, sometimes at personal cost. David Hazelhurst recalled:\n\n<blockquote>One day in 1963, when I was editor of ''Drum'' magazine, Alf Khumalo walked into my office carrying a picture. It showed a burly policeman delivering a vicious kick between the legs of reporter Harry Mashabela from behind. Such was the power of the kick you could see the shape of his boot exploding through the front of Mashabela' trousers.\n\nIt was the year of the jackboot of John Vorster, habeas corpus had disappeared, the 90-day-detention without trial Act had given policemen a license to kill and assault behind closed doors with impunity.\n\nThe police hated journalists \u2013 and photographers in particular, for their pictures portrayed the truth about an evil system, and Kumalo, despite warnings, risked a severe beating to take the Mashabela picture. He had tried to sell it to several papers with no success.<ref name='Nat Nakasa Award'>{{cite news | first= | last= | author2= | title=Veteran photographer Alf Kumalo wins the 2005 Nat Nakasa Award | date= | publisher=SA National Editors Forum | url =http://www.sanef.org.za/nat_nakasa_award/ | work = | pages = | accessdate = 17 May 2007 | language = }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHazelhurst splashed the picture across two pages of ''Drum''.\n\nOver the years Kumalo photographed and documented many of the historic moments in recent South African history. These include the [[Treason Trial]], the [[Rivonia Trial]], the emergence of [[Black Consciousness Movement|Black Consciousness]], the [[Soweto uprising|Student Uprising]] of 1976 and the [[Convention for a Democratic South Africa|Codesa]] talks. This was despite numerous periods of detention, arrests and official [[harassment]].\n\nHis work has appeared in international newspapers like ''[[The Observer]]'', ''The New York Times'', ''[[New York Post]]'', and the ''[[Sunday Independent (South Africa)|Sunday Independent]]''. Locally, he also worked for ''Drum'' magazine and the long-defunct ''[[Rand Daily Mail]]''.<ref name='5 decades'>{{cite news | first=Mandisi | last=Majavu | author2= | title=Alf Khumalo: 5 decades in photos | date=5 November 2004 | publisher=SA Information | url=http://www.southafrica.info/what_happening/news/features/khumalophotos.htm | work= | pages= | accessdate=16 May 2007 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184707/http://www.southafrica.info/what_happening/news/features/khumalophotos.htm | archive-date=30 September 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTo assist the upcoming generation of South African photographers, Kumalo opened a photographic school in [[Diepmeadow, Gauteng|Diepkloof]] [[Soweto]] in 2002.<ref name=Weber /> The school offers nine-month courses designed to train photographers from disadvantaged backgrounds.<ref name='Interview'>{{cite news | first=Izane | last=Mynhardt | author2= | title=Interview: Alfred Khumalo | date= | publisher=New Visions Africa | url =http://www.newvisionsafrica.com/files2/volume%2013/interview.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 16 May 2007 | language = }}</ref>\n\nHe died on 21 October 2012.<ref>http://www.iol.com</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n* ''Mandela: Echoes of an era'' / by Alf Kumalo; text by Es'kia Mphahlele, Penguin Books, 1990, {{ISBN|0-14-014316-5}}\n* ''Alf Kumalo: South African Photographer'', Itala Vivan & Alf Kumalo, Leonardo arte, {{ISBN|88-7813-384-1}}\n*''Through My Lens: A Photographic Memoir'', Alf Kumalo, text by Tanya Farber, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0624044673}}\n*''8115: A Prisoner's Home'', Alf Kumalo; text by Zukiswa Wanner, Penguin Books, 2010, {{ISBN|9780143538370}}\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Solo exhibitions===\n\n* 2004 \u2013 59th Session of the United Nations General Assembly in New York City \u2013 a collection of his life's work \u2013 the exhibition was much acclaimed<ref name='Interview' />\n\n===Group exhibitions===\n\n* 2001 \u2013 ''Soweto \u2013 A South African Myth'' \u2013 Photographs from the 1950s (by Alf Khumalo, [[Ernest Cole (photographer)|Ernest Cole]] and [[J\u00fcrgen Schadeberg]]). The core of the exhibition is the [[Soweto uprising|student uprising]] of 1976. This includes some of [[Peter Magubane]]'s work.\n* 2002 \u2013 ''Shooting Resistance: South African Photography 1976 \u2013 1994'' \u2013 The exhibition documented the period of upheavals that began with the student-led [[Soweto uprising]] of 1976 and culminated in the collapse of the apartheid regime and the introduction of democratic elections in 1994. Included were photographs by Alf Kumalo, [[J\u00fcrgen Schadeberg]] and [[Peter Magubane]].\n* 2006 \u2013 ''Madiba: Public and Private'' \u2013 Nelson Mandela Foundation, Johannesburg. Works by photographers Alf Kumalo and [[J\u00fcrgen Schadeberg]]. Schadeberg's photos are of the public images of [[Nelson Mandela|Mandela]] from the 1950s, during the [[Defiance Campaign]] and before Mandela's imprisonment, while Kumalo's are of Mandela's private life, particularly of his family. Many of Kumalo's pictures were taken of Mandela's growing family, to send to Mandela in jail.\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2004 \u2013 South African [[Order of Ikhamanga]] in Silver for \"his excellent contribution to documentary photography and journalism in South Africa\".<ref name='National Orders'>{{cite news| title=Alfred Khumalo| date=10 November 2004| publisher=S A Government| url=http://www.info.gov.za/aboutgovt/orders/2004/khumalo.htm| accessdate=16 May 2007| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171009/http://www.info.gov.za/aboutgovt/orders/2004/khumalo.htm| archivedate=30 September 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 South African National Editors Forum \"Nat Nakasa Award for Media Integrity\" for displaying \"courageous journalism throughout his professional career\".<ref name='Nat Nakasa Award' />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kumalo, Alf}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Amajuba District Municipality]]\n[[Category:South African photographers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n", "name_user": "Discott", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alf_Kumalo"}
{"title_page": "Csongr\u00e1d County", "text_new": "{{About|the current administrative entity called Csongr\u00e1d county|the historical county|Csongr\u00e1d County (former)|the town|Csongr\u00e1d}}\n{{Expand Hungarian|Csongr\u00e1d megye|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|County of Hungary}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Csongr\u00e1d County\n| native_name             = <small>''Csongr\u00e1d megye''</small>\n| native_name_lang        = hu\n| settlement_type         = [[Counties of Hungary]]\n| image_skyline           = {{Photomontage\n  | photo1a = Maros river embankment, near to Mako - causeway.jpg{{!}}Maros river embankment near Mak\u00f3 \n  | photo2a = \u00d3pusztaszer Rotunda.JPG{{!}}\u00d3pusztaszer National Heritage Park\n  | photo2b = Cathedral of Szeged2.jpg{{!}}Cathedral of Szeged\n  | spacing = 2\n  | position = center\n  | color_border = white\n  | color = white\n  | size = 255\n  | foot_montage = Descending, from top: [[Mure\u0219 (river)|Maros]] river embankment near [[Mak\u00f3]], [[\u00d3pusztaszer National Heritage Park]], and [[Szeged Cathedral|Cathedral of Szeged]]}}\n| image_flag              = FLAG-Csongrad-megye.svg\n| image_shield            = HU Csongr\u00e1d megye COA.svg\n| image_map               = HU county Csongrad.svg\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Csongr\u00e1d County within Hungary\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{HUN}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of Hungary|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Southern Great Plain]]\n| seat_type               = County seat\n| seat                    = [[Szeged]]\n| parts_type              = [[Districts of Hungary|Districts]]\n| parts                   = 7 districts\n| p1 = [[Csongr\u00e1d District]]\n| p2 = {{nowrap|[[H\u00f3dmez\u0151v\u00e1s\u00e1rhely District]]}}\n| p3 = [[Kistelek District]]\n| p4 = [[Mak\u00f3 District]]\n| p5 = [[M\u00f3rahalom District]]\n| p6 = [[Szeged District]]\n| p7 = [[Szentes District]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_title \t          = President of the General Assembly\n| leader_name \t          = B\u00e9la Kakas\n| leader_party            = [[Fidesz]]-[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]]\n| area_total_km2          = 4262.71\n| area_rank               = [[Counties of Hungary|12th in Hungary]]\n| population_as_of        = 2015\n| population_total        = 406205<ref>[http://nepesseg.com/csongrad/ nepesseg.com, population data of Hungarians settlements]</ref>\n| population_rank         = [[Counties of Hungary|8th in Hungary]]\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal codes in Hungary|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 66xx \u2013 69xx\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Hungary|Area code(s)]]\n| area_code               = (+36) 62, 63\n| iso_code                = {{mono|HU-CS}}\n|website                 = {{URL|http://www.csongrad-megye.hu/}}\n}}\n'''Csongr\u00e1d''' ({{lang-hu|Csongr\u00e1d megye}} {{IPA-hu|\u02c8t\u0361\u0283o\u014b\u0261ra\u02d0d|}}), set to be renamed '''Csongr\u00e1d-Csan\u00e1d''' from 2020<ref>[https://www.delmagyar.hu/szeged_hirek/csongrad-csanad_lesz_a_megye_neve_2020-tol/2534751/ Csongr\u00e1d-Csan\u00e1d lesz a megye neve 2020-t\u00f3l]</ref> is the name of an administrative county ([[Counties of Hungary|comitatus]] or ''megye'') in southern [[Hungary]], straddling the river [[Tisza]], on the border with [[Serbia]] and [[Romania]]. It shares borders with the Hungarian counties [[B\u00e1cs-Kiskun]], [[J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok]] and [[B\u00e9k\u00e9s (county)|B\u00e9k\u00e9s]]. The administrative centre of Csongr\u00e1d county is [[Szeged]]. The county is also part of the [[Danube-Kris-Mures-Tisa]] euroregion.\n\n==History==\nOn October 3, 2017, the Hungarian Parliament passed a resolution to rename Csongr\u00e1d County to Csongr\u00e1d-Csan\u00e1d, which will take effect on June 4, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vasarhelyilokalpatriotak.blog.hu/2017/10/04/csongrad_csanad_megye_az_uj_elnevezes|title=Csongr\u00e1d - Csan\u00e1d megye, az \u00faj elnevez\u00e9s v\u00e9delm\u00e9ben|last=Harmat \u00c1rp\u00e1d|first=P\u00e9ter|date=October 5, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The resolution was submitted by J\u00e1nos L\u00e1z\u00e1r, then-Minister of the Prime Minister's Office, who called the renaming symbolic as more than a dozen settlements in the area still share Csan\u00e1d County's identity.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://hvg.hu/itthon/20171003_uj_neve_van_csongrad_megyenek|title=\u00daj neve van Csongr\u00e1d megy\u00e9nek|date=October 3, 2017|work=HVG|accessdate=April 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThis county has a total area of {{convert|4263|sqkm|sqmi|0|abbr=on}} \u2013 4,58% of Hungary.\n\nThe area of Csongr\u00e1d County is flat. It has a high number of sunshine hours and excellent soil, which makes it the most important agricultural area of Hungary. Its most famous products are [[paprika]] from [[Szeged]] and [[onion|onions]] from [[Mak\u00f3]], but grain, vegetables, and fruits are also significant. Half of the onions, paprika, and vegetables produced in Hungary are from Csongr\u00e1d. The county is also rich in oil and natural gas.\n\nThe highest point is \u00c1sotthalom (125 m), the lowest is Gy\u00e1lar\u00e9t (78 m; lowest point of Hungary).\n\n===Neighbours===\n* [[J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok County]] in the North.\n* [[B\u00e9k\u00e9s County]] in the East.\n* {{ROU}} and {{SRB}} in the South \u2013 [[Timi\u0219 County]] and [[North Ba\u010dka District]]\n* [[B\u00e1cs-Kiskun County]] in the West.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Csongr\u00e1d County (2011 census)\n|label1 = [[Catholic Church]]\n|value1 = 39.4\n|color1 = DarkOrchid\n|label2 = [[Greek Catholicism]]\n|value2 = 0.4\n|color2 = MediumOrchid\n|label3 = [[Calvinism]]\n|value3 = 7.0\n|color3 = DodgerBlue\n|label4 = [[Lutheranism]]\n|value4 = 0.8\n|color4 = DeepSkyBlue\n|label5 = [[Orthodoxy]]\n|value5 = 0.2\n|color5 = FireBrick\n|label6 = [[Judaism]]\n|value6 = 0.1\n|color6 = Orange\n|label7 = Other religions\n|value7 = 1.7\n|color7 = Chartreuse\n|label8 = [[Irreligion|Non-religious]]\n|value8 = 21.8\n|color8 = Honeydew\n|label9 = [[Atheism|Atheists]]\n|value9 = 1.6\n|color9 = Grey\n|label10= Undeclared\n|value10= 27.0\n|color10= Black\n}}\n{{see also|Demographics of Hungary}}\nAfter the end of the [[Ottoman Hungary|Ottoman occupation]] in 1715, the county was nearly uninhabited, with a [[population density]] of less than 5/km<sup>2</sup>. In the 18th and 19th centuries, the county was repopulated by ethnic [[Hungarians]] from the relatively overpopulated northern and western counties of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]].<ref>Changing ethnicities in Hungary (map+data+assay) (K\u00e1roly Kocsis, Zsolt Bottlik, [[Magyar Tudom\u00e1nyos Akad\u00e9mia|MTA]] F\u00f6ldrajztudom\u00e1nyi Kutat\u00f3int\u00e9zet, [[Budapest]] 2009, {{ISBN|978-963-9545-18-2}}, {{ISBN|978-963-9545-19-9}})</ref> According to the 2001 census, the county is home for 423,826 people (216,936 people live in [[counties of Hungary|urban counties]]) with a population density is 100/km<sup>2</sup>. It has a [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] majority.<ref>[http://www.nepszamlalas.hu/eng/volumes/06/06/tabeng/toc1.html Csongr\u00e1d county (2001 census), English]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, it had a population of 406,205 and the [[population density]] was 95/km\u00b2.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! County population<ref>n\u00e9pess\u00e9g.com, ''[http://nepesseg.com/csongrad/ \"Csongr\u00e1d megye n\u00e9pess\u00e9ge 1870-2015\"]''</ref>\n! Change\n|-\n| 1949\n| 429,083\n|align=\"right\"| n/a\n|-\n| 1960\n|{{increase}} 434,046\n|align=\"right\"| 1.16%\n|-\n| 1970\n|{{increase}} 445,220\n|align=\"right\"| 2.57%\n|-\n| 1980\n|{{increase}} 456,300 (record)\n|align=\"right\"| 2.49%\n|-\n| 1990\n|{{decrease}} 438,842\n|align=\"right\"| -3.83%\n|-\n| 2001\n|{{decrease}} 433,344\n|align=\"right\"| -1.25%\n|-\n| 2011\n|{{decrease}} 417,456\n|align=\"right\"| -3.67%\n|}\n\n===Ethnicity===\nBesides the Hungarian majority, the main minorities are the Roma (approx. 5,000), Romanian (1,500), German (1,300) and Serb (1,300).\n\nTotal population (2011 census): 417,456<br />\nEthnic groups (2011 census):<ref>[http://www.ksh.hu/nepszamlalas/tablak_teruleti_06 1.1.6. A n\u00e9pess\u00e9g anyanyelv, nemzetis\u00e9g \u00e9s nemek szerint \u2013 Friss\u00edtve: 2013.04.17.; Hungarian Central Statistical Office] {{in lang|hu}}</ref>\nIdentified themselves: 367,193 persons:\n*[[Hungarians]]: 355,554 (96.83%)\n*[[Romani people in Hungary|Gypsies]]: 4,720 (1.29%)\n*Others and indefinable: 6,919 (1.88%)\n\nApproximately 59,000 persons in Csongr\u00e1d County did not declare their ethnic group on the 2011 census.\n\n===Religion===\n{{see also|Religion in Hungary}}\nReligious adherence in the county according to the 2011 census:<ref>2011. \u00c9VI N\u00c9PSZ\u00c1ML\u00c1L\u00c1S, 3. Ter\u00fcleti adatok, 3.6 Csongr\u00e1d megye, {{in lang|hu}} ''[http://www.terezvaros.hu/testuleti/nepsz2011-3/pdf/nepsz2011_03_06.pdf]''</ref>\n\n*Catholic \u2013 165,955 ([[Roman Catholicism in Hungary|Roman Catholic]] \u2013 164,060; [[Hungarian Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] \u2013 1,855);\n*[[Reformed Church in Hungary|Reformed]] \u2013 29,289; \n*[[Evangelical-Lutheran Church in Hungary|Evangelical]] \u2013 3,488;\n*[[Eastern Orthodoxy in Hungary|Orthodox]] \u2013 923;\n*[[History of the Jews in Hungary|Judaism]] \u2013 263;\n*Other religions \u2013 7,278; \n*[[Irreligion|Non-religious]] \u2013 90,836; \n*[[Atheism]] \u2013 6,585;\n*''Undeclared'' \u2013 112,839.\n\n==Regional structure==\n[[File:Csongr\u00e1d districts.png|thumb|right|350px|District of '''Csongr\u00e1d County''']]\n{